#Repost 1st @sunburnfestival and  featured directly in two of their after movies (need to find the other video, saw it on the screen playing at the music festival!)
.
But even reaching here at the @sunburnfestival has been a journey in itself! 
.
The first time I heard about the music festival was during my teen years, haha but I was too young, broke and scared (from a very strict family) to be able to attend the festival, actually I guess back then didn’t even match the age criteria lol. Or never had the pass, then when had the passes, didn’t have the guts to ask at home. Or the friend ditched. It just never worked out basically. 
.
Then after some years, when I was finally ready and waiting, it got banned in #Goa 🤭.
.
Then @timeout72official came after a year or 2 & became the first music festival of my life. But I was always waiting for @sunburnfestival .
.
Fast forward to now from struggling to get the passes or pay for it. To directly attending it as a #contentcreator & a #influencer , getting the Partner tag with even backstage access. This girl has definitely come a long way. I just want to thank you all for giving me the strength to keep working and reach here🙏🏻. 
.
Keep following your vision everyday.  One day you will reach there!
.

.

Shell 🐚 island in #Goa | SAVE & SHARE w your Goa gang today!
.
As part of the #GoaWithAGoan #reelseries , in Ep 2 - I’m taking you all to this heaven in Vasco my home😭❤️. 
.
This island located on the Zuari River, is actually disconnected from the water & is only accessible as the this spot in the river has 2 opposite currents which on low tide make a clearing to walk on IN BETWEEN THE RIVER…YES😭❤️. I’m so in awe with nature and it’s capabilities!
.
Important instructions before visiting:
1. Do not litter the place. Carry only yourself and your phone.
2. Make sure you don’t stay for long. The pathway to the island gets created by 2 different currents of the river opening the pathway - it’s not for long. We got into trouble. Risky for non experienced travellers.
.
Follow @style_in_a_suitcase & @travelrealindia for some #realGoa recommendations & experiences like these! 🐚
.

The Monday blues got to me today, so I turned the whole world colorful 🌈🤷🏻‍♀️🪄
.
Genuinely what a crazy day, in fact a few crazy days since it restarted my Meditation (IT TAKES ALOT OF DISCIPLINE THATS WHY ITS CALLED SADHANA - meaning discipline) and honestly in today’s unconscious world where people praise hustle culture & even see their worth in working or feeling free to contact you outside work hours - it gets to you.
.
I even restarted working out cause I started reading about health! And how muscles loss or not having muscles in your body can cause many diseases even diabetics!!
.
Challenging & Doing a few more things that I never did before TOTALLY out of my comfort zone + clearing age old to do list tasks that I have been procrastinating.
.
Working and growing my clients business 10x using my social media & marketing skills. From personal branding to product businesses - since I love my clients - they always get a priority!
.
Instagram is already a handful + Recently even started and have been consistent on YouTube! And my oh my oh - this transition is so hectic - trying to grow from 0 in a new platform isn’t for the weak.
.
Trying to keep up with my love with my Instagram, Travelling, coming up with creative ideas.
.
The hustle is real! And sometimes it sure gets to you!
In all this also add the personal growth- because I truly believe what’s not growing is already dead. And in the mid of all this chaos on my plate - trying to be there for self. Healing my inner child. 
.
Oh what a discomfort- but oh what a growth 💞.
I would do it all over again, bring it on week! And you?
.

Tried the Viral Thick Chocolate Shake in #Goa !DM me this reel for the location!
.
This cafe has been around for like 10 years, I recall the first time I heard about it during college and went to check it out - it was closed 🫢) tried 2 times - I didn’t even have a bike then so was traveling by bus as a student - so IMAGINE - I was like let it be and never went back.
.
To fast forward finding it almost 6years later !
.
My review: 6.5 to 7 out of 10
-I thought it’s  Cab-B (as in Cadbury) but it’s not made of it. 
- loved the thickness of the shake (it’s my fav aspect)
- I have had better shakes for the same price range or like 150. 
- But all in all none the less - a very good option for students and friends to just chill & have a shake / a bite right in the centre of the Panjim city!
.
Who would you go here with?
.

Shine so bright it burns their effing eyes 👀 
.
It took some time but I finally left all the fake layers of life such as people, be it family, relatives, haters, college bullies from my class, work colleagues or bosses that needed me to play small or dim my light.
.
It took some time to fully feel “no fucks given” quite literally to actually accept and hold space for myself to LET myself shine ✨ bright and full of magic 🪄 
.
Whoever uncomfortable was never your person anyway, be it whoever, doesn’t matter! Because it’s normally the closest people you consider to yourself.
.
It definitely took time, but I finally found my wings, my flight, and my light, I FOUND HER 💖 everything was part of the story because all along, to add on to her strength, personality, because only through pain you can achieve power 💖 I LOVE HER 💖
.

latestPosts.caption:
#Goa always surprises me 🤯SAVE & SHARE to tell more people about this rich #cultureofGoa !
.
Background:

Gadyanchi Jatra is a unique festival Honouring Betal in #GoaIndia , a revered local deity, and also a form of #KalBhairav ! 
.
Goa is said to be filled with ghosts & spirits & locals through this festival seek protection from the King of Ghosts Betal 👑 
.
It happens every 3 years in May (17th May was this year) at a village named #poinguinim in #Canacona Goa.
.
The festival follows a three-year cycle: the first year sees the ritual of ‘Jevni’, the second features a procession called ‘Takaa’ where permission to hold the Zatra is taken, and then the third culminates in the grand Jatra.
.
According to the legend, Betal conquered 12 kingdoms in Goa causing alot of destruction & deaths, when he reached this village the head of the village pleaded him to stay and make it his abode, a Betal agreed, promising to protect it in exchange for a festival in his name every three years.
.
In the days leading up to the Jatra, sacred items like Taranga, Satri, and Pillkucho (peacock feathers) are brought to the temple. Two massive tree trunks (Khaamb), about 40-45 feet tall, are erected in front of the Betal temple, with a large wooden spindle (Raat) mounted on them.
.
On the day of the Jatra, Betal’s image is adorned in a traditional style that has remained unchanged for generations. Four men known as Gade, dressed in white dhotis and turbans, dance with swords and a red cloth in hand. They are ritually pierced with metal hooks into their back muscles-and other devotees (including young kids) are pierced with needles on their stomachs.
.
All this is done with ancient wisdom the village posses. It is said that in doing so, no blood comes, and post the ritual the they are taken care of in the temple. Where they heal miraculously. 
.
Since Lord Betal is a fierce form of energy, this area was also known for #tantra . A Bali of hen is given, it is also said that decades ago - one of the Gade would fall from the Wheel, as Bali. That has been stopped now.
.
I have been to various zatras- but this will remain a special one for sure!
.
[gadyanchi zatra Goa, Betal, Kal Bhairav]
